KIRTLAND AIR FORCE BASE USED ABSORBANT MATERIAL FOR CLEAN UP.

VEHICLE #1 PROCEEDING EAST ON U.S. ROUTE 30, INSIDE LIMITS OF BELLEVUE, OHIO.  DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN ACCIDENT IN TRAFFIC, STRUCK REAR OF VEHICLE AHEAD OF HIM, IMPACT CAUSED LOAD TO SHIFT FORWARD, AND RUPTURED ONE 20 GALLON PLASTIC DRUM OF PRODUCT IN NOSE OF TRAILER.  POLICE AND FIRE DEPT. SUMMONED, CHEMTREC CONTACTED, AND USE OF LIME PRODUCT COMPLETED TO NEUTRALIZE THE LIQUID WHICH HAD LEAKED FROM TRAILER ONTO ROADWAY.  IN ADDITION, INTERIOR OF TRAILER NEUTRALIZED, LOAD REMOVED AND RELOADED TO ENSURE INSPECTION OF ALL DRUMS AND PRODUCT, PLUS RESTACK PRODUCT WHICH WAS ORIGINALLY SQUEESED, BUT NOT LEAKING IN NOSE OF TRAILER.  COMPLETED OPERATION DONE APPROXIMATELY 1000 HOUR 7/6/90.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGING FAILURE OF ANY KIND.  THIS INCIDENT RESULTED FROM POOR DISPATCHING.  OUR DISPATCH DEPT. SENT A NEW EMPLOYEE, WHO HAD NOT YET BEEN TRAINED ON MC306 CARGO TANKS, TO UNLOAD THE LOAD AT CIBRO PETRO.  THE TRAILER WAS PARKED ON AN INCLINE AND THE DRIVER OPENED ALL THE INTERNAL VALVES AT ONCE WHICH ALLOWED FUEL TO FLOW OUT THE TOP VENTS AND INTO THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE AND SPILL ONTO THE GROUND.  AGAIN, THE TRAILER PERFORMED EXACTLY AS IT WAS DESIGNED, THE DRIVER USED THE WRONG PROCEDURE FOR UNLOADING ON HILLS. NEW YORK STATE DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED OF THIS INCIDENT AND SUPERVISED THE CLEANUP.

ON 7-19-90, DRIVER HOOKED UP HIS HOSE TO CUSTOMERS UNLOADING LINES, CUSTOMERS EMPLOYEE GAVE THE OKAY FOR THE DRIVER TO STATR UNLOADING.  THE DRIVER PUT 20-25 POUNDS OF AIR PRESSURE ON TANK TO OFF LOAD TRHE PRODUCT. DRIVER STAYED BY THE DELIVERY HOSE FOR APPROX 10 MINS. TO ASCERTAIN THAT THERE WERE NO LEAKS IN CONNECTIONS AND THAT PRODUCT WAS UNLOADING CORRECTLY.  DRIVER THEN WENT TO THE CAB ON HIS TRUCK TO DO SOME PAPERWORK. A FEW MINUTES LATER, THE UNLOADER ADVISED THE DRIVER THE PRODUCT HOSE HAD REPTURED.  THE DRIVER GOT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND CLOSED ALL PRODUCT VALVES. THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED INTO A CONCRETE HOLDING TANK ( NO PRODUCT REACHED THE GROUND OR WATER).  THE HOLDING TANK DRAINED DIRECTLY INTO THE CUSTOMERS WASTE WATER TANK WHERE WASTE IS STORED FROM CUSTOMERS MANUFACTURING PROCESS.  THE PRODUCT WILL BE TREATED IN THE WASTE TANK. RECOMMENDATIONS: CONSIGNEES AND/OR SHIPPERS SHOULD BE REQUIRED BY REGULATIONS TO FURNISH THEIR OWN HOSES, PUMPS, AIR COMPRESSORS AND PERSONNEL FOR LOADING AND UNLOADING OF ANY PRODUCT.  THE SHIPPERS AND CONSIGNEE'S ARE TRYING TO SUPPLEMENT THEIR WORKK FORCE WITH CARRIERS PERSONNEL, AND PLACING TOO MUCH RESPONSIBILITY ON THE DRIVERS. THE DELIVERING DRIVERS ARE NOT FAMILIAR WITH SHIPPERS AND/OR CONSIGNEES UNLOADING PROCEDURES, I.E. VALVES, TANKS, ATE., BY REQUIRING THE SHIPPERS AND/OR CONSIGNEES WOULD BE RESPONSIBLE TO OPEN OR CLOSE ALL OF THEIR VALVES, KNOW WHETHER THEIR RECEIVING TANKS WOULD HOLD THE PRODUCT. BY REQUIRING THE SHIPPERS AND CONSIGNEES TO FRUNISH THE HOSES, PUMPS, AIR COMPRESSOR'S, ETC., THAT COULD CAUSE A SPILL BY MALFUNCTIONING AND ELIMINATE THE POSSIBILITY OF CONTAMINATION OF PRODUCT AND REACTION BETWEEN THE DIFFEREDNT PRODUCTS IN HOSES THAT CAUSED DETERIORATION OF HOSES AND CAUSING HOSE OR PUMP FAILURE.

column168: ON JULY 9, 1990, TONAWANDA TANK TRANSPORT SERVICE, INC. WAS CONTRACTED BY GENERAL ELECTRIC SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 156 CIRCLE FREEWAY DRIVE, CINCINNATI, OHIO TO FURNISH A TANKER AND ONE DRIVER TO ASSIST IN THE REMOVAL OF PCB OIL FROM A TRANSFORMER AND TRANSPORT THE PRODUCT TO THE GENERAL ELECTRIC SERVICE CENTER IN CINCINNATI, OHIO.  THE TRANSFORMER WAS LOCATED AT THE TIMET CORPORATION, 100 TITANIUM WAY, TORONTO, OHIO. AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT, PCB OIL WAS BEING PUMPED FROM A BELOW GROUND LEVEL TRANSFORMER INTO THE TANKER, WHICH WAS PARKED ON THE FLOOR ABOVE. SEE ATTACHED DIAGRAMS 1 AND 3.  THE MATERIAL WAS BEING PUMPED WITH A PACER CENTRIFUGAL PUMP WITH A 20 FOOT SECTION OF HOSE FROM THE TRANSFORMER TO THE PUMP AND A 40 FOOT SECTION OF HOSE FROM THE PUMP TO THE TANKER. DURING THE PUMPING PROCESS, OIL WAS FOUND TO BE SEEPING FROM AROUND THE PUMP'S FILLER PLUG (SEE PUMP SPECIFICATION SHEET ATTACHED).  TONAWANDA TANK TRANSPORT SERVICE, INC. PERSONNEL SHUT THE PUMP OFF, CLOSED THE VALVE AT THE TRANSFORMER AND TIGHTENED THE FILLER PLUG.  THE TOP OF THE FILLER PLUG BROKE OFF (SEE ATTACHED DIAGRAM 3) ALLOWING PCB OIL TO ESCAPE INTO THE VAULT AREA.  AN ESTIMATED VOLUME OF 10 GALLONS WAS RELEASED AND THREE OPERATORS WERE SPRAYED WITH MATERIAL. PERSONNEL AND THE AFFECTED AREAS WERE CLEANED UP IMMEDIATELY.  ALL SURFACE AREAS WERE WASHED DOWN TWICE BY GENERAL ELECTRIC PERSONNEL USING POWER CLEANER 155.  ALL CLEANING MATERIALS AND CONTAMINATED CLOTHING WAS PLACED IN 55 GALLON DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL BY GENERAL ELECTRIC. THE PERSONNEL SPRAYED WITH OIL EXPERIENCED SLIGHT SKIN IRRITATIONS. SHOWERS WITH SOAP AND WATER ELIMINATED THIS EFFECT AND NO ONE HAS REQUIRED ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION OR TREATMENT. THIS INCIDENT WAS THE DIRECT RESULT OF THE FAILURE OF THE PUMP DRAIN PLUG. IT IS UNDETERMINED IF THE FAILURE WAS THE RESULT OF AN INHERENT PRODUCT DEFECT OR STRESS FROM REGULAR USE.  REGULAR PREVENTATIVE MAINTENANCE IS PERFORMED ON THE PUMP AND A PRE-ASSIGNMENT INSPECTION PRIOR TO USE ON JULY 9, 1990 REVEALED NO MECHANICAL PROBLEMS. WE HAVE AUTHORIZED SOME ADDITIONAL CLEANING OF THE CONTAMINATED AREA AND, PENDING THE RESULTS OF THE TESTS TO BE CONDUCTED THIS WEEK, EXPECT TO DECLARE THE SITE CLEARED IN ACCORDANCE WITH 40 CFR, PART 761 PCB SPILL CLEANUP POLICY. FINALLY, WE ARE WORKING IN CONCERT WITH GENERAL ELECTRIC SERVICE CENTER PERSONNEL AND OUR OWN CONSULTING FIRM TO ESTABLISH ADDITIONAL PROCEDURES TO LIMIT THE POSSIBILITY OF FUTURE PROBLEMS. WE HAVE ALREADY IMPLEMENTED REVISED STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES WHICH WILL 1) PROVIDE FOR AMPLE PLASTIC SHEETING TO COVER THE ENTIRE AREA OF POTENTIAL CONTAMINATION DURING PUMPING OPERATIONS, 2) MANDATE THAT ALL HOSES BE DRAINED PRIOR TO THE REPAIR OR ADJUSTMENT OF PUMPS, HOSES, ETC. DURING PUMPING OPERATIONS, AND WE ARE INVESTIGATING EQUIPMENT CHANGES TO REDUCE THE RISKS OF MECHANICAL FAILURE.

EXCESS FLUID WAS ABSORBED ON TRAILER FLOOR WITH ABSORBENT GRANUALS.  LOST PRODUCT WAS MINIMAL - DRUM WAS UNVENTED - THEREFORE LOSS WAS A SLOW LEAK FROM A SMALL HOLE.  LETTER SENT TO VENDOR AND TO CONSIGNEE ADVISING OF SHIPPER'S RESPONSIBILITY TO BLOCK LOAD, AND TO TERMINAL ADVISING OF DRIVER RESPONSIBILITY TO INSPECT LOAD FOR PROPER BLOCKING PRIOR TO MOVING LOAD.

OUR DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO THE CUSTOMER'S TANK. HE PROCEEDED TO ATTACH THE TRANSFER HOSES. HE IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF THE PUMP AND WHEN DISCONNECTING THE HOSES TO ATTACH THEM PROPERLY PRODUCT THAT WAS IN THE HOSES SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND.  IT WAS ABSORBED USING ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND THEN CLEANED UP.  OUR DRIVER THEN PROCEEDED TO COMPLETE HIS TRANSFER WITHOUT FURTHER DIFFICULTY.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR UNLOADING AT DESTINATION AND PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE.  AS OUR VEHICLE WENT EMPTY THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANK OVERFLOWED.  THE RECEIVER HAD INCORRECTLY ESTIMATED THE ROOM IN HIS STORAGE TANK.  THE CUSTOMER TOOK CARE OF THE CLEAN UP.

OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT DESTINATION AND WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY.  HE PROCEEDED TO PRESSURIZE HIS TRAILER FOR TRANSFER OF THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE AND AT THIS TIME NOTED A DRIP OF PRODUCT FROM THE BELLY OF HIS TRAILER.  THE RECEIVER PLACED A CONTAINER UNDER THE DRIP TO CATCH THE MATERIAL AND THE DELIVERY PROCEEDED UNTIL FINISHED.  OUR TRAILER WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIR.

column168: WHEN THE GROUND CREW IN ARGENTINA BEGAN TO UNLOAD THE CARGO FROM THE PLANE THEY DISCOVERED THE SPILL.  THE GROUND CREW APPLIED SAWDUST TO THE SPILL AND THE PLANE WAS FLOWN BACK TO MIA AIRPORT WHERE THE ACID SOLUTION SPILLED WAS NEUTRALIZED BY OHM CORP.  THE PLANE WAS DISASSEMBLED TO THE AIRFRAME IN THE CARGO SECTION TO INSURE THROUGH CLEANING AND FACILITATE INSPECTION FOR ANY POSSIBLE CORROSION.  THE PLANE WAS INSPECTED BY THE FAA APPROVED REPAIR STATION NARCAM IN MIAMI AND THE FAA LOCAL INSPECTOR AFTER CLEANING AND WAS RELEASED FOR USE.  THE HAZARDOUS WASTE GENERATED IN THIS OPERATION WAS DISPOSED OF IN AN APPROVED EPA ROUTE BY THE OHM CORP. PACKAGING USED FOR THE SHIPMENT WAS DOT APPROVED SPEC 34 DRUMS PALLETIZED 36 TO A PALLET AND STRETCH WRAPPED, THE PALLET PATTERN USED IS 4X3 STACKED 3 HIGH ON A PALLET.  THE AIRLINE LOADS 4 PALLETS, SINGLE PALLET HIGH ON A UNITIZED LOAD DEVICE AND NETS THEM FOR SAFE TRANSIT.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAKAGE WAS PUNCTURES TO THE LOWER LIP AREA OF THE DRUMS.  THE THREE DRUMS WERE PUNCTURED BY THE CARDO NET ANCHOR CLIPS SOMETIME DURING THE FLIGHT. THE PALLETIZED LOAD MUST HAVE SHIFTED SIGNIFICANTLY IN TRANSIT AS THE DRUMS NEEDED TO LEAVE THE PALLET TO BE PUNCTURED BY THE ANCHORS. PALLETIZED LOADS THAT ARE LOADED 4 PALLETS TO A UNITIZED LOAD DEVICE AND ARE RESTRAINED WITH A NET USUALLY DO NOT SHIFT IN THIS MANNER.  WE WILL REVIEW THE USE OF ADDITIONAL STRETCH WRAP ON THE PALLETS AND PROVIDE A PROTECTIVE CARDBOARD SHEET FOR THE BOTTOM.  THIS WILL PROVIDE ADDITIONAL PROTECTION AGAINST PUNCTURES AND LOAD SHIFTS.  OUR PLANT PERSONNEL IN ARGENTINA VISITED THE AIRPORT A DAY LATER AND SAID THAT AT THE AIRPORT THE FREIGHT WAS NO LONGER PALLETIZED AND STRETCH WRAPPED AND ONLY ONE PALLET WAS PRESENT.  THEY WERE NOT ABLE TO DETERMINE WHY THIS WAS SO.  THE CARRIER SAID THE FREIGHT WAS MOVED AS IT WAS GIVEN TO THEM BY PEPSI, SO WE HAVE REPORTED THE INCIDENT AS PACKED THAT WAY. ADDENDUM: WHILE THIS IS THE SAME SHIPMENT OF DRUMS THAT WAS INVOLVED IN THE MIAMI SPILL ON 7/6/90 THE DAMAGE CAUSED BY THAT INCIDENT WAS NOT THE SAME AS FOUND WITH THE PUNCTURED DRUMS.  THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS INSPECTED AFTER ARRIVAL TO OUR PLANT IN ARGENTINA AND THE FOLLOWING WAS FOUND:  SOME IMPACT DAMAGE TO SOME CONTAINERS AND SMALL CRACKS IN THE HANDLE AREA OF 4 DRUMS.  SINCE THIS WAS ALL TOP SURFACE DAMAGE IT RESULTED IN NO SPILLAGE. (IT IS SIMILAR TO THE DAMAGE SEEN IN MIAMI, LAB TESTING SHOWS THE HANDLES CRACK AT 10 TO 12 FT DROP HEIGHT).  WHILE IN OUR OPINION SOME POOR JUDGEMENT WAS USED REGARDING THE CHOICE MADE ON THE REMAINING 37 DRUMS SUITABILITY FOR SHIPMENT AFTER THE MIAMI FALL, THE LEAKERS SHOW NO SIMILAR DAMAGE AND WERE PROBABLY NOT PUNCTURED BEFORE LOADING.  WE HAVE NO WAY TO DETERMINE IF THE LEAKERS CAME FROM THE GROUP OF PAILS THAT WERE DROPPED IN MIAMI OR NOT,  BUT THE PUNCTURES ARE A TOTALLY DIFFERENT FAILURE MODE THAN THE RUPTURES IN MIAMI, AND IF PUNCTURED IN MIAMI THEY WOULD HAVE EMPTIED BEFORED RELOADING.

column168: IN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING THE AIRCRAFT IN MIAMI BECAUSE OF A PLANE CHANGE IN ROUTE TO ARGENTINA, 50 OF THE PALLETIZED DRUMS FELL OFF OF THE ULD (UNITIZED LOAD DEVICE) TO THE TARMACK LIFT BELOW.  THE PRINCIPLE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT WAS A LOAD SHIFT ON THE PALLETS OR ULD DURING TRANSIT. THE AIRLINE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED THE MIA FIRE DEPARTMENT ALONG WITH THE DADE COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES MANAGEMENT AND FLIGHT CONTROL MIA. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT CONTACTED CHEMTREC FOR INFORMATION ON THE HAZARD INVOLVED AND RECOMMENDED CLEANUP ORGANIZATIONS.  ENVIROPACT MIAMI WAS SELECTED AND RESPONDED.  ENVIROPACT SUBSEQUENTLY CLEANED AND DECONTAMINATED THE SITE AS PER THE DADE COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL RESOURCES AGENCY'S INSTRUCTIONS.  THE REMAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WILL BE DISPOSED OF BY THE OHM CORPORATION AT A SUITABLE EPA DISPOSAL SITE AFTER LABORATORY TESTING IS COMPLETED TO DEFINE ITS NATURE.  THE BALANCE OF THE CARGO INVOLVED IN THE SPILL (50 MINUS 13, OR 37 DRUMS) WAS INSPECTED BY ENVIROPACT AND RELEASED TO ARROW AIR FOR SHIPMENT TO ARGENTINA.  PEPSI PACKAGING USED FOR THE SHIPMENT WAS DOT APPROVED SPEC. 34 DRUMS PALLETIZED 36 TO A PALLET AND STRETCH WRAPPED, THE PALLET PATTERN USED IS 4X3 STACKED 3 HIGH ON A PALLET.  THE AIRLINE LOADS 4 PALLETS, SINGLE PALLET HIGH, ON A UNITIZED LOAD DEVICE AND NETS THEM FOR SAFE TRANSIT.  TO REDUCE THE POSSIBILITY OF LOAD SHIFTS OF THIS TYPE OF THE ULD, THE PALLET RESTRAINT WRAPS WILL BE INCREASED AND THE PALLETIZING PATTERNS WILL BE REVIEWED.

ROY STOPPED ON THE OHIO TURNPIKE NEAR STATE ROUTE 57 AND DISCOVERED THAT THE LID AND CLAMP RING HAD COME OFF THE 500 GALLON TOTE TANK OF PAINT STRIPPER.  ROY FOUND THE RING AND LID ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER AND PUT IT BACK ON AND HAND TIGHTENED THE CLAMP BOLT. column168: OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE MARINE CORPS AIR STATION TO MAKE HIS DELIVERIES AND DISCOVERED THIS SHIPMENT HAD TURNED OVER WITH TWO CASES FALLING AGAINST A PALLET.  WHEN THESE TWO CASES STRUCK THE PALLET, THE SIDES OF THREE ONE GALLON CANS WERE DENTED FORCING OPEN THEIR LIDS ALLOWING THE SPILL.  MARINE CORPS PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED THE BASE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM. ON THEIR ARRIVAL A COMPLETE CHECK WAS MADE BY BOTH UNITS AT WHICH TIME THEY ADVISED RECEIVING PERSONNEL THERE WAS NO DANGER AND LEFT THE AREA.  MARINE CORPS PERSONNEL HANDLED THE CLEAN UP.  OUR INVESTIGATION DETERMINED SITUATION COULD HAVE BEEN PREVENTED BY STACKING NO MORE THAN TWO HIGH IN  TRAILER TO PREVENT FALLING OVER.  IMMEDIATE ACTION BEING TAKEN IN EFFORT TO PREVENT A FUTURE SITUATION.

column168: THE VAN WAS OBSERVED LEAKING WHEN THE YARD CHECK WAS PERFORMED.  THE CARRIER NOTIFIED TRIDENT AND OHM.  OUR #800 RESPONSE TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO ADDRESS THE SPILL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED TO THE VAN BY OHM AND THE SHIPMENT WAS MOVED TO THE TRIDENT WAREHOUSE FOR UNLOADING AND CLEANUP. THE SPILL INVOLVED ONE DRUM OF PRODUCT.  SEVERAL OTHER DRUMS WERE SPLASHED AND WERE CLEANED OR HAD THEIR OVERPACKS REPLACED.  THE CAUSE OF THE ACCIDENT WAS A DAMAGED FLOOR BOARD PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  WE WILL INSTITUTE A BETTER VAN INSPECTION PROGRAM AT OUR PLANT TO PREVENT A REPEAT OF THIS TYPE OF FAILURE. DRIVER WAS LOADING DRUM ONTO TRUCK VIA LIFT GATE.  DRUM BEGAN TO SLIDE OFF LIFTGATE.  DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO STOP DRUM.  WEIGHT OF DRUM BEGAN TO PULL DRIVER OFF TRUCK.  IN KEEPING WITH SAFETY POLICIES, DRIVER RELEASED ONE HAND HOLD ON DRUM.  DRUM CONTINUED TO SLIDE AND FELL FROM LIFT GATE.  DRUM LANDED ON SIDE AND INSTANTLY RUPTURED (LID POPPED OFF).  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY EXITED TRUCK AND RIGHTED DRUM.  SPILL WAS LIMITED TO APPROXIMATELY 30 GALLONS.  DRIVERS NEXT STEP WAS TO DIKE THE SPILL AT FURTHEST POINT.  LIQUID WAS RUNNING DOWN GRADE FROM TRUCK.  ONCE DIKE WAS ESTABLISHED, DRIVER NOTIFIED CONSIGNEE OF INCIDENT.  EXTRA MAN POWER WAS CALLED TO SCENE POST HASTE.  CLEAN-UP BEGAN WITHIN 45 MINUTES OF SPILL. LIFTGATE HAS SLIGHT ANGLE WHEN RAISED.  LIFT GATE IS TO REPAIRED (REINFORCED OR REPLACED).  NEW RULING BY TRANSPORTER STATES, ANY TIME LIFT GATE IS KNOWN TO BE NEEDED, TWO PEOPLE SHALL BE USED TO MAKE PICK-UP.

column168: RECEIVED IMPORT SHIPMENT FROM JAPAN ( PACKAGED ACCORDING TO IMO).  CARGO WAS MANIFESTED AND LABELED FOR NITRIC ACID, 2031.  WE DISCOVERED IT WAS ACTUALLY NITRIC ACID, RED FUMING, UN2032.  WHILE FORKLIFT DRIVER WAS MOVING CARGO, WOOD BOX FELL OFF FORKLIFT AND DROPPED APPROXIMATELY 4 FEET. WHEN HE UPRIGHTED PACKAGE HE NOTICED LEAKAGE.  WE IMMEDIATELY EVACUATED PREMISES TAKING PAPERS OF ALL HAZARDOUS ON PREMISES AND CALLED 911 (EMERGENCY # FOR FIRE DEPT.).  WE ALSO CALLED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY BUT WHEN FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED THEY SUGGESTED WE USE A DIFFERENT COMPANY WHICH RESPONDS QUICKER (SEE 23E).  ON 7/12 WE NOTICED A SMELL AND CALLED EMERGENCY RESPONSE COMPANY BACK OUT TO CHECK AND THEY FOUND 4 MORE CRACKED BOTTLES.  WE HAVE REVIEWED OUR HAZARDOUS PROCEDURES AND THE INCIDENT HAS MADE ALL EMPLOYEES AWARE OF THE EXTREMELY FRAGILE NATURE OF SUCH SHIPMENTS.

column168: CYLINDERS WERE LOADED ON THE VAN TRAILER AT THE DOCK IN PREPARATION FOR SHIPMENT THE FOLLOWING DAY.  EMPLOYEES ON DUTY WERE IN THE BREAKROOM (ON BREAK) WHEN THE CHLORINE ALARM SOUNDED AT 1750 HOURS.  AFTER SEEING THE PROBLEM OF CHLORINE ESCAPING FROM THE FUSE PLUG, PERSONNEL PROTECTION EQUIPMENT WAS DONNED, INCLUDING SELF CONTAINED BREATHING APPARATUS, AND THE LEAK WAS STOPPED USING EMERGENCY "A" KIT.  THE LEAK WAS SEALED 1800 HOURS.  REMAINING PRODUCT WAS PURGED FROM THE CYLINDER SHORTLY AFTERWARD INTO OUR MANUFACTURING PROCESS.  IT IS MY DETERMINATION THAT WATER FROM THE VALVE TESTING PROCESS HAD GOTTEN IN A SMALL CREVICE WHERE THE LEAD MEETS THE BRASS OF THE FUSE PLUG CAUSING SOME DETERIATION OF THE LEAD AND COMBINED WITH THE INCREASED PRESSURE DUE TO THE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE FORCED THE FUSIBLE MATERIAL OUTWARD.

column168: WASTE SPILL OF RO WASTE ALKALINE LIQUID NOS ON JULY 23, 1990, AT 9:30AM. ENVIRITE'S DRIVER EXPERIENCED A DISCHARGE OF APPROXIMATELY 2.50 GALLONS OF THE ABOVE-REFERENCED WASTE MATERIAL ONTO PAVEMENT AT THE GENERATOR'S SITE DURING A ROUTINE PICK-UP.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN THE TRAILER'S VACUUM LOADING SYSTEM AND UTILIZED EQUIPMENT SUPPLIED BY THE GENERATOR TO CONTAIN AND COLLECT SPILL.  THE DRIVER THEN REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE CANTON ENVIRITE FACILITY.  THIS INCIDENT WAS APPARENTLY CAUSED BY EXCESSIVE FOAMING OF THE WASTE DURING A ROUTINE VACUUM LOADING OPERATION.  FOAM IS GENERATED BY THE PRESENCE OF SURFACTANTS AND/OR PRESSURE (VACUUM) INSIDE THE VESSEL.

column168: DRIVER #1 REPORTS HE WAS NORTHBOUND ALREADY INTO CURVE ON M-35 NEAR 26TH AVE. S. WHEN HE OBSERVED A WHEEL FROM HIS TRAILER RISE OFF THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER COULD NOT CONTROL THE TRACTOR-TRAILER AS IT ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE, WENT OVER THE RIGHT CURB & CAME TO A STOP OFF THE ROADWAY AFTER APPROXIMATELY 130 FT. THE ESCANABA PUBLIC SAFETY DEPT. INVESTIGATED THE ACCIDENT WITH THE MICH. STATE POLICE, MICH. MOTOR CARRIER DIVISION, MICH. DNR, HARVEY OIL CO. OFFICIALS.  CONTAINMENT OF SPILLED CARGO WAS BEGUN BY U.P. ENVIRONMENTAL OF BARK RIVER, MICH.  CLEANUP RESPONSIBILITY WAS FINALIZED BY DELTA ENVIRONMENTAL OF MINNEAPOLIS, MN. AND NORTHERN A-1 SERVICES OF KALKASKA, MICH.  THESE FIRMS WERE BROUGHT IN BY HARVEY OIL'S INSURANCE CARRIER FEDERATED MUTUAL OF OWATONNA, MN.  THE DRIVER JACK MACDONALD HAS LOGGED OVER ONE MILLION MILES W/O A CHARGEABLE OFFENSE UNTIL THIS INCIDENT.  NO MECHANICAL FAILURES WERE FOUND WITH THE EQUIPMENT. CONCLUSION:  DRIVER WAS TICKETED FOR DRIVING TOO FAST FOR CONDITIONS. RECOMMENDATION:  TANK TRAILERS SHOULD CONSTRUCTED WITH A LOWER CENTER OF GRAVITY AND MORE PROTECTION BE AFFORDED FOR PIPING UNDER TRAILERS WHICH MAY PREVENT SPILLAGE IN FUTURE INCIDENTS.

THE BATTERY THEN TURNED ON IT'S SIDE, SPILLING SULFURIC ACID. APPROXIMATELY 8 OUNCES SPILLED.  DOUG HODGE (HANDLER) NOTICED AND ACIDIC SMELL AND CAME TO GET ME.  I PUT GLOVES ON AND MOVED THE CONTAINER TOAN ISOLATED AREA OF OUR WAREHOUSE.  I THEN LOOSENED THE CLAMPS (2 EACH SIDE, 8 TOTAL) AND REMOVED THE TOP HALF OF CONTAINER.  THERE WAS A BATTERY ON IT'S SIDE ALONG WITH A SMALL COLLER AND AN INSTRUMENT.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED WITHIN THE PACKAGE.  I POURED VERMICULATE OVER THE BATTERY AND SPILLED LIQUID SO IT WOULD SOLIDIFY THE SPILLED LIQUID.  RECEIVING FACILITY - GROUND WATER TECHNOLOGY, C/O GO GAS STATION, 308 N. BIG HORN AVE., WORLAND WY. 82401.

column168: PACKAGE DISCOVERED AT SORTING FACILITY, IN THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS HOLDING AREA. THE OUTER BOX WAS WET, AND HAD A STRONG ODOR.  FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED NO DAMAGE TO THE INNER CANS.  ADDITIONALLY, THERE WAS NO EXTERNAL LEAKAGE.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED FOR DISPOSITION OF THE PAKAGE.

WHEN SORTING THIS PACKAGE AT THE DESTINATION TERMINALS, THE PACKAGE WAS NOTICED TO BE WET NEAR THE BOTTOM.  INSIDE INSPECTION REVEALED NUMEROUS PLASTIC BOTTLES AND ONE GLASS BOTTLE.  THE CONSIGNEE WAS CONTACTED WHO STATED THAT THEY BELIEVED THE GLASS BOTTLE WAS A CORROSIVE.  THE PACKAGE WAS NOT MARKED, LABELED OR IN ANY WAY IDENTIFIED AS A DANGEROUS GOOD.  I THEN CONTACTED THE SHIPPER AND REQUESTED A MSDS FOR THE PRODUCTS INSIDE. THE SHIPPER WAS VERY HELPFUL AND REFERRED ME TO THE COMPANIES TRAFFIC HEADQUARTERS WHO FAXED ME THE NECESSARY FORMS.  REVIEW OF THE FORMS CONFIRMED THAT ONE OF THE PRODUCTS WAS A CORROSIVE.  JIM HOWLETT WITH TURCO LATER CALLED AND SAID HE HAD BEEN INFORMED OF THE SITUATION AN RESEARCHED THE INCIDENT.  HE HAD DETERMINED THE LAB HAD PACKAGED THE MATERIALS  UP AND DID NOT THINK ONE PINT WAS REQUIRED TO BE OFFERED AS A DANGEROUS GOOD.  JIM FURTHER STATED HE IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED PROCEDURES TO ENSURE ALL THEIR LABS NOT CLOSE BOXES BEFORE TAKING THEM TO SHIPPING. ADDITIONALLY, HE NOW REQUIRES THE MSDS FORMS TO BE PROVIDED WITH ALL CHEMICALS THAT MAY BE SHIPPED.  I THEN NOTIFIED ROBERTA PASTORE AT THE LAX CASFO OFFICE.  SHE INSTRUCTED ME TO FILE THE NECESSARY REPORTS ALTHOUGH THE FAA WOULD NOT BE PHYSICALLY INSPECTING THE SHIPMENT.

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: AS WITH MOST OF OUR INCIDENTS, THERE WAS NO PACKAGE FAILURE.  OUR DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE SERVICE STATION AND CONNECTED THE HOSE TO THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK.  APPARENTLY THE DRIVER DID NOT PROPERLY LOCK THE 4" EVERTITE FITTING ONTO THE FILL PIPE AS FUEL SPRAYED OUT AROUND THE GASKET BETWEEN THE FITTING AND THE FILL PIPE.  A RE-ATTACHMENT OF THE FITTING PROVIDED NO FURTHER PROBLEMS.  THE ORIGINAL ESTIMATE OF 30 GALLONS IS PROBABLY OVERSTATED AS THE FUEL SPRAYED OUT AND COVERED A 4" BY 8" AREA, BUT DID NOT SOAK IN FAR.  THIS WAS AN EXPERIENCED DRIVER WHO MADE THE MISTAKE OF TURNING HIS BACK ON THE HOSES WHEN HE OPENED THE VALVES TO UNLOAD.  NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONVERSATION WAS NOTOFIED AND SUPERVISED THE CLEAN-UP.  THEY ALSO ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #9004608 TO THIS INCIDENT.

column168: VII AND VIII ABOVE:  THERE WAS NO FAILURE ON THE PART OF ANY EQUIPMENT. THIS INCIDENT INVOLVED THE OVERFILLING OF AN UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK. AN EMPLOYEE OF GARDEN TIME TOLD OUR DRIVER THAT THE TANKS WERE MANIFOLDED TOGETHER AND THAT THEY HAD ROOM FOR 15,000 GALLONS. OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND SENT A REPRESENTATIVE TO THE SCENE TO OVERSEE THE CLEANUP.  A REFERENCE # 9004487 WAS ASSIGNED TO THIS INCIDENT. column168: ON JULY 12, 1990, AT ABOUT 9:55 AM., TRUCK DRIVER JOHN HILLAGE NOTICED AN ODOR WHILE AT A TRAFFIC LIGHT THAT INTERSECTS CENTRAL AVE. AND BALLTON RD. IN THE CITY OF SCHENECTADY, N.Y.  HE THOUGHT IT MIGHT POSSIBLY BE COMING FROM HIS TRAILER (#484).  HE PULLED INTO THE MOHAWK MALL PARKING LOT IN AN ISOLATED AREA TO INVESTIGATE. HIS INVESTIGATION TURNED UP A DRUM OF XYLENE SLOWLY LEAKING FROM A PINHOLE IN THE SIDE OF THE DRUM.  HE IMMEDIATELY FLIPPED THE DRUM OM ITS SIDE WITH THE PINHOLE IN THE UPPER MOST POSITION.  HE CALLED HIS PLANT MANAGER AND INFORMED HIM OF THE INCIDENT.  HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO CALL CLARDON POOL SERVICE (2199 CENTRAL AVE., SCHENECTADY, N.Y. 12304 TELEPHONE (518-370-0592) AND HAVE THEM BRING A BAG OF ABSORBENT AND THAT A RESPONSE TEAM WAS BEING DISPATCHED. HIS RESPONSE TEAM TRANSFERRED THE XYLENE DRUM INTO A NEW 55 GAL. STEEL DRUM WITHOUT ANY FURTHER RELEASE OF LIQUID.  THE ABSORBENT SPREAD ON SPILL BY JOHN HILLAGE WAS SHOVELLED INTO AN OPEN RING TOP DRUM.  THE EMPTY XYLENE DRUM, PARTIAL XYLENE DRUM AND SPILL CLEANUP DRUM WERE RETURNED TO MONARCH CHEMICALS, INC.  THE MATERIAL WAS PROPERLY DISPOSED OF BY SOLVENTS AND PETROLEUM, INC. AFTER WEIGHING THE DRUMS IN QUESTION IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 1.5 GALLONS HAD LEAKED. SPILLAGE MATERIAL WAS CONFINED TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.

AT APPROXIMATELY 5:45 PM JULY 8, 1990.  FOUR CARS, GLCX 3001, GLCX 3003, PSPX 23527 AND PSPX 23542, WERE INVOLVED IN A DERAILMENT AT PASADENA YARD OF PTRA RESULTING IN CARS GLCX 3001 AND PSPX 23542 LYING ON THEIR SIDE.  I WAS NOTIFIED AT 6:10 PM ABOUT THE DERAILMENT AND THAT PSPX 23542 WAS LEAKING.  ALL FOUR CARS WERE CARRING CYCLOHEVANE.  WHEN I ARRIVED AT PASADENA YARD, THE PASADENA FIRE DEPT. HAD PLACED A GARBAGE CAN TO CATCH THE DRIP THAT WAS COMING OUT OF THE VACUME BREAKER ON PSPX 23542.  MR LEROY ROBINSON OF INTERCONTINENTAL TERMINAL HAD BEEN CALLED AND RESPONSE TEAM OF PHILLIPS HAD BEEN CALLED. ALL DECIDED THAT THE DRIP WOULD STOP AS SOON AS THS CAR WAS UPRIGHTED. WHICH IT DID. WHEN CAR WAS UPRIGHTED ABOUT 11:00 PM JULY 8, 1990.  TRACK WAS REPAIRED AFTER CARS WERE RERAILED. PRODUCT EVAP

column17: CARMAN J A TRUCKING CO INC
column168: VII AND VIII ABOVE, NO PACKING FAILURE INVOLVED.  FOX RUN PARC IS A TRUCK STOP JUST OFF THE NY STATE THRUWAY (I87) IN COXSACKIE, NY.  WE HAD TWO TRAILERS DELIVERING AT THE SAME TIME, ONE DELIVERING GASOLINE AND THE OTHER DELIVERING DIESEL FUEL.  BOTH TRUCKS WERE POSITIONED NEXT TO EACH OTHER AS ALL THE STORAGE TANKS AT FOX RUN PARC ARE IN A ROW.  AS THE TRUCK THAT WAS UNLOADING GASOLINE GOT NEAR THE END OF HIS DELIVERY, THE FUMES FROM THE GASOLINE TANK VENT WERE SUCKED INTO THE AIR INTAKE ON THE OTHER TRACTOR THAT WAS UNLOADING DIESEL FUEL.  THIS CAUSED THE ENGINE OF THE TRACTOR TO RACE AWAY WILDLY, CAUSING ITS PRODUCT PUMP TO OVER PRESSURE THE DELIVERY HOSES.  AS A RESULT, THE DISCHARGE HOSE BLEW OFF THE PUMP ON OUR TRACTOR. FUEL THEN FLOWED ONTO THE PARKING LOT AND DOWN INTO A DRAINAGE DITCH.  AN INSPECTION OF THE HOSE FITTINGS REVEALED NO FAILURE HAD OCCURRED.  WE HAVE SINCE USED THE SAME PUMP & HOSE WITH NO PROBLEM.  NEW YORK STATE DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND INVESTIGATED THE SPILL AS WELL AS SUPERVISING THE CLEAN-UP.  THEY ASSIGNED A REFERENCE NUMBER OF 9004773 TO THIS INCIDENT.  A REPORTING FORM THAT IS DESIGNED FOR PETROLEUM TRANSPORTERS WOULD BE MOST HELPFUL.  THIS FORM SEEMS TO BE DESIGNED ONLY FOR INCIDENTS THAT RESULT FROM ACCIDENTS.

THE FRT WAS LODGED BETWEEN TWO WOOD PALLETS ON THE TRLR FLOOR.  HE ATTEMPTD TO MOVE ONE PALLET TO GET AT THE SHIPMENT OF NITRIC ACID BUT THE MOVEMENT OF SKID BROKE THE CONTAINER AND THE NITRIC ACID LEAKED ONTO TRAILER FLOOR AND CONCRETE PAD BELOW. WE SPOKE TO A ROBERTA BUCKNER W/BAXTER AND SHE ADVISED WE SHOULD BUT BAKING SODA ON REMAINING RESIDUE OF ACID AND FLOOD THE AREA WITH WATER. ON 7/12/90 AT 14:30 HOURS, AIRCO DRIVERS HAD COMPLETED OFF-LOADING LIQUID HYDROGEN AT SOMERS IN WATERBURY, CT.  THE DRIVERS WERE PREPARING TO DISCONNECT FROM TANK WHEN THEY NOTICED SMALL LEAK AT "T" CONNECTION ON LIQUID LINE TO LIQUID LEVEL GAUGE.  DRIVER STOPPED LEAK BY FORCING SMALL WOODEN STICK INTO OPENING.  THE DRIVERS CALLED FOR AIRCO CUSTOMER SERVICEMAN AT 15:00 HOURS TO REPAIR LEAK.  SERVICE MAN ARRIVED AND ATTEMPTED TO REPAIR LEAK WITHOUT SUCCESS.  A CALL WAS PLACED TO AIRCO GASES CORPORATE OFFICE AT 17:30 FOR ASSISTANCE.  AIRCO TEAM ARRIVED AT SOMERS AT 22:00 HOURS.  AFTER ASSESSING SITUATION, THE TEAM INSTRUCTED THE SERVICEMAN ON HOW TO REPAIR LINE.  THE TEAM EXPLAINED PROCEDURE TO FIRE AND POLICE OFFICIALS ON SIGHT.  PREPARATION FOR REPAIR BEGAN AT 23:45 AND REPAIR WAS SUCCESSFULLY COMPLETED AT 01:00 HOURS 7/13/90.

column168: AN EMPLOYEE WAS UNLOADING A 40' SEMI-VAN CONTAINING 4 150# SULFUR DIOXIDE CYLINDERS ALONG WITH OTHER CYLINDERS.  DURING THE UNLOADING PROCESS, THE CYLINDER WAS KNOCKED OVER.  THE SAFETY CAP CAME OFF AND THE VALVE BENT. PRODUCT THEN STARTED LEAKING FROM THE SAFETY AREA.  THE DEFORMATION OF THE VALVE CAUSED THE SAFETY TO NOT SEAT PROPERLY.  THE CYLINDER WAS PLACED IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION TO PREVENT LIQUID FROM COMING OUT AND ALLOW THE VAPOR PRESSURE TO DISPERSE.  ALL EMPLOYEES WERE EVACUATED FROM THE GENERAL AREA. AS THE CYLINDER WAS IN A WELL VENTILATED AREA, IT WAS LEFT WHERE IT WAS UNTIL JONES CHEMICAL ARRIVED.  JONES CHEMICAL BEING A SUPPLIER, HAD THE PROPER LEAK KIT TO PUT ON THE CYLINDER.  APPROXIMATELY 5 HOURS AFTER THE INITIAL ACCIDENT, THE CYLINDER WAS REMOVED FROM THE PREMISES.  TOTAL PRODUCT LOSS WAS 3.5#.  THE EMPLOYEE THAT INHALED A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF VAPOR WAS TAKEN TO A LOCAL MEDICAL FACILITY FOR PRECAUTIONARY CHECK-UP.  AFTER THE CHECK-UP, HE RETURNED TO WORK THE FOLLOWING DAY WITH NO PROBLEMS.  PROP CYLINDER HANDLING PROCEDURES WERE REVIEWED WITH THE EMPLOYEE.  10-22-90 LISA EMMART 9616-963-7929) INHALED FUMES, CHECKED AT MEDICAL FACILITY AS PRECAUTION.  NO LOST TIME.  NOT AN EVACUATION, JUST MOVED PEOPLE AWAY FROM DROPPED CYLINDER.

column168: WE WERE REQUESTED BY UNO-VEN TO EFFECT PUMP OUT OF UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS AT THE NOTED SITE, WE RESPONDED WITH TWO OF OUR TRACTOR-TRAILER UNITS ( GASOLINE TANKERS MC306) WITH TWO RESPECTIVE DRIVERS.  ONE DRIVER WAS ON GROUND OPERATING PUMP OUT PIPES, HOSES AND VALVING ALONG WITH TRACTOR PUMP PTO.  SECOND DRIVER WAS TOP SIDE OF TRAILER TO MONITOR CAPACITY OF PRODUCT BEING PLACED INTO OUR TRAILER COMPARTMENTS AS WE EFFECTED THE PUMP OUT.  THERE WAS MISCOMMUNICATION BETWEEN THE TWO DRIVERS AS TO WHEN TO SHUT THE PUMP AND PRODUCT FLOW, AS A RESULT THE TRAILER COMPARTMENT OVERFILLED WITH RESULT BEING THAT A SPILLAGE OF APPROX 50 TO 80 GALLONS OF GASOLINE OCCURRED.  OUR DRIVERS RESPONDED BY SHUTTING DOWN ALL EQUIPMENT, PLACING ABSORBENT PADS AND SAUSAGES DOWN TO CONTAIN SPILLED PRODUCT. (WE CARRY EMERGENCY SPILL KITS ON OUR UNITS), PHONED THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT AND OUR LOCAL SUPERVISOR WHO IN TURN CALLED OUR CORPORATE SAFETY DEPT.  OHIO EPA WAS NOTIFIED (INCIDENT ID# 7-18-3680) AND WE ALSO NOTIFIED NRC (REPORT# 32894).  LOCAL FIRE DEPT RESPONDED, FLUSHED NEARBY SEWERS (PRECAUTIONARY-NO PRODUCT OR RESIDUALS/VAPORS WERE FOUND IN THE DRAINS OF SEWERS).  WE USED SAMSEL CO. OF CLEVELAND TO EFFECT GROUND CLEAN-UP WITH TWO 55 GALLON DRUMS OF ABSORBENT MATERIAL/GASOLINE BEING THE RESIDUAL OF THE CLEAN-UP.  THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT DECIDED FOR PRECAUTIONARY MEASURES, TO EVACUATE A PRE-SCHOOL NEXT DOOR TO THE UNOCAL 310 FACILITY. READINGS, ETC WERE PERFORMED AND NO ACTUAL DANGER EXISTED, NO FUMES OR READINGS WERE DETECTED OTHER THAT AT THE ACTUAL SPILL SITE.  THE INCIDENT WAS UNFORTUNATELY MITIGATED BY IMPROPER COMMUNICATION AND MISUNDERSTANDING BETWEEN OUR TWO DRIVERS WHO WERE ON SITE PERFORMING THE PUMP THEMSELVES MISCOMMUNICATED  AS TO WHEN TO SHUT THE PUMP OFF AND THUSLY THE PRODUCT FLOW.  BOTH DRIVERS HAVE BEEN INTERVIEWD CONCERNING THE INCIDENT AND ARE AWARE THAT PROPER AND TIMELY COMMUNICATION BETWEEN BOTH OF THEM WAS IMPERATIVE TO THE SITUATION AND A PROPER PROCEDURAL CONTROL OF THE PUMP/LOADING PROCESS.  WE HAVE QUARTERLY DRIVER SAFETY MEETINGS THROUGHOUT OUR SYSTEM AND WILL DETAIL THIS INCIDENT FOR ALL OF THE DRIVERS IN OUR SYSTEM IN HOPES OF IMPARTING PROPER PROCEDURES AND THE NEED FOR ALL INVOLVED TO COMMUNICATE AND RESPOND IN TIMELY AND SAFE MANNERS.

column42: HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S. OR ORM-E, LIQUID OR SOLID, N.O.S.
column168: THE APTUS SPILL RESPONSE TEAM REMOVED 2-55 GALLON DRUMS OF MATERIAL, ROCK AND SOIL, UNTIL LAB TESTS SHOWED NO TRACE OF ASKAREL REMAINING. SEE ATTACHED REPORT ON JULY 22, 1990, TRI-STATE MOTOR TRANSIT TRUCK NO. 601, DRIVEN BY RANDALL BRANAM, WAS INVOLVED IN AN INCIDENT THAT RESULTED IN THE RELEASE OF ASKAREL INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  ACCORDING TO MR BRANAM, THE FOLLOWING IS WHAT OCCURRED:  THE TRI-STATE VEHICLE WAS LADEN WITH MATERIAL DESCRIBED ON THE ATTACHED MANIFEST DESTINED FOR THE APTUS FACILITY AT COFFEYVILLE, KS. AT APPROXIMATELY 16:25 HOURS, MR BRANAM ARRIVED AT THE JUNCTION OF US 166 AND US69 WHICH IS ABOUT 6 MILES WEST OF BAXTER SPRINGS, KS.  THIS IS A 4-WAY STOP INTERSECTION CONTROLLED WITH STOP SIGNS.  AFTER COMING TO A COMPLETE STOP, HE STARTED TO PULL TRUCK TO THE NORTH.  THIS VEHICLE PROCEED THROUGH THE INTERSECTION AT SPEED CAUSING MR BRANAM TO APPLY HIS BRAKES SUDDENLY.  MR BRANAM PULLED INTO AN ABANDONED TRUCK STOP THAT SETS ON THE SOUTHWEST CORNER OF THE INTERSECTION TO IONSPECT THE LOAD.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT UPON BRAKE APPLICATION, A TRANSFORMER NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER SHIFTED ABOUT 6-10" FORWARD.  A TIE DOWN CHAIN THAT HAD BEEN PLACED BETWEEN TOW CEREMIC BUSHINGS CAUSED ONE OF THESE BUSHINGS TO BREAK WHEN IT CAME INTO CONTACT/STRUCK THE CHAIN. ASKAREL WAS FLOWING OUT OF THE BROKEN BUSHING INTO THE CONTAINMENT PLAN. A SMALL AMOUNT OF ASKAREL WAS ALSO DRIPPING ONTO A PIECE FO WOOD USED TO BLOCK AND BRACE, FLOWING TO THE END ON THE WOOD AND ONTO THE GROUND.  LESS THAN 1 PINT WAS RELEASED ONTO THE GROUND.  MR BRANAM PUT HIS PROTECTIVE CLOTHING ON AND PROCEEDED TO WIPE THE WOOD WITH PAPER TOWELS TO KEEP THE MATERIAL FROM DRIPPING ONTO THE GROUND.  THE TRAILER PAN HAD A SUBSTANTIAL AMOUNT OF WATER IN IT CAUSED BY RUNNING THROUGH A RAIN.  THE OIL RUNNING OUT OF THE TRANSFORMER WAS FLOATING ON THIS WATER.  MR BRANAM RELEASED AIR FROM HIS TRACTOR AIR BAGS TO ALLOW THE TRAILER TO REST LOWER IN THE FRONT. THIS BROUGHT ALL LIQUID MATERIAL TO THE FRONT OF THE TRAILER AND PREVENTED ANY FROM POSSIBLE LEAKING OUT THE TAILGATE ON THE PAN.  ALL DEBRIS DRUMS WERE FULL WHICH PREVENTED MR. BRANAM FROM PUMPING THE TRANSFORMER DOWN.

column168: WHILE AT TSMT'S NORTH EST, MD TERMINAL FACILITY INVESTIGATING POSSIBLE LOAD SHIFT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT A VENT CAP ON TOP OF A 300 GALLON CAPACITY POLY ETHYLENE TOTE WAS ALLOWING A SMALL AMOUNT OF MATERIAL TO BE RELEASED.  THE DRIVER APPLIED A NEUTRALIZING AGENT (BAKING SODA) TO THE LIQUID.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED AND ELECTED TO SEND A SPILL RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE (O.H. MATERIALS).  THE LEAKING TOTE WAS REPAIRED AND THE LOAD PROCEEDED ON TO DESTINATION WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT.  NO MATERIAL WAS RELEASED INTO THE ENVIRONMENT.  THE RQ WAS NOT MET, HOWEVER UPON THE RECOMMENDATION OF AT&T A REPORT WAS MADE TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  REPORT NO. 30868.

JAMES GEUMONALS, DRIVER, LOADED THE FREIGHT AT OUR DOCK AND NOTICED THAT THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE WAS DAMP.  HE LOADED THE FREIGHT IN HIS VAN. UPON DELIVERY THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING WORSE.  THE CONSIGNEE REFUSED THE SHIPMENT.  HE BROUGHT IT BACK TO OUR DOCK AND TURNED IT OVER TO THE DOCK PERSONNEL.  THE DOCK PERSON, BOB CHILDRESS, PLACED THE CHEMICAL IN HAZ MAT AREA. column168: TANK CAR, UTLX 99099 RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING BY TWO UNION PACIFIC RAILRAOD SPECIAL AGENTS CONDUCTING A ROUTINE YARD INSPECTION ACCOUNT ODOR.  SENIOR SPECIAL AGENTY-HAZARDOUS MATERAILS, T. M. ROBINSON, INSPECTED THE CAR AND DETERMINED THAT IT WAS LAEKING FROM THE GAUGING DEVICE PACKING GLAND NUT AND THE MANWAY NOZZLE GASKET.  THE LEAK AT THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS SECURED, BUT THE MANWAY NOZZLE GASKET COULD NOT BE UNDER THE 125 P.S.I.G. VAPOR PRESSURE. THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ARRANGED FOR THE TANK CAR TO BE TAKEN TO A NEARBY CHEMICAL PLANT WHERE THE REMAINING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA VAPOR WAS FLARED OFF.  THE CAR WEAS THEN SENT TO AN OWNER DESIGNATED REPAIR FACILITY IN TEXAS.

HILL DETERMINED THAT POSIBILITY OF MORE THAN ONE LEAKING 55 GALLON DRUM DUE TO NO BLOCKING ALLOWING LOAD TO SHIFT. column168: UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, A.J. GARDNER, WAS NOTIFIED BY A SWITCH CREW WORKING IN EASTBOUND BOWL #4 TRACK THAT THEY HAD DETECTED AN ODOR AND SUBSEQUENTLY LOCATED SUBJECT TANK CAR, ACFX 12227, WHICH WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP AT A SLOW RATE. INVESTIGATION BY MR. GARDNER DEVELOPED THAT TANK WAS DRIPPING DUE TO AN OPEN BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE.  MR. GARDNER SECURED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND STOPPED LEAK.  THE MINOR AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WHICH LEAKED ONTO THE GROUND EVAPORATED IMMEDIATELY WITH NO POOLING OR RESIDUE REMAINING.  THE TANK CAR, WHICH WAS MISSING A FLAMMABLE LIQUID PLACARD ON THE "B" END OF CAR, WAS REPAIRED AND RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.  A NEW PLACARD WAS APPLIED TO CAR BEFORE RELEASE.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, A.J. GARDNER, WAS REQUESTED TO RESPOND TO WESTBOUND BOWL #27 WHERE TANK CAR GATX 41236 WAS NOTED VENTING ANHYDROUS AMMONIA FROM DOME AREA OF CAR.  THE VAPOR VENTING WAS NOTED BY A SWITCHMAN IN THE BOWL.  INSPECTION BY MR. GARDNER DEVELOPED THAT VAPORS WERE LEAKING FROM LIQUID LINE PLUG AT A RELATIVELY SLOW RATE.  A CLOSER OBSERVATION HELPED DETERMINE THAT THE LIQUID LINE VALVE WAS SLIGHTLY OPEN AND THE LIQUID LINE PLUG WAS NOT TIGHTLY SEATED. MR. GARDGER TIGHTENED LOOSE VALVE WHEEL TO SEAL VALVE AND SEATED LIQUID LINE PLUG BY TIGHTENING IT, WHICH STOPPED THE VAPOR LEAK.  TANK CAR WAS REPAIRED AND RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT-HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, D.L. WHITELEY, DISCOVERED LIQUID LEAKING FROM TOFC CSXZ 239812, DISPLAYING CORROSIVE PLACARDS, MOVING ON FLAT CAR MP 838050.  INTERIOR INSPECTION BY MR. WHITELEY NOTED PLYWOOD BULKHEAD INTACT AND IN GOOD ORDER.  THE WOODEN PALLET LOCATED IN THE LEFT REAR CORNER OF THE TRAILER AND CARRYING FOUR 55 GALLON DRUMS HAD COLLAPSED.  THIS ALLOWED DRUMS TO REST IN UNEVEN POSITIONS RESULTING IN CHIMES OF DRUMS RUBBING AGAINST SIDES OF ADJACENT DRUMS CAUSING FAILURES.  THIS UNEVEN CONDITION RESULTED IN THE LOSS OF THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF ONE 5 GALLON DRUM AND MINIMAL LOSS FROM FIVE OTHER 55 GALLON DRUMS.  CONTENTS OF TRAILER WERE TRANSFERRED FOR DELIVERY TO CONSIGNEE.  CLEAN-UP OF TRAILER AND FLAT CAR WAS HANDLED BY UNION PACIFIC AND CHAPMAN CHEMICAL, PORTLAND.  MR. WHITELEY NOTIFIED CHEMTREC, MIKE WEST, CHAPMAN CHEMICAL, MEMPHIS, TN AND DONALD PETTY, CHAPMAN CHENICAL, PORTLAND, OR.

30 JULY, 1990 AT 3:35 AM DRIVER MICHAEL HINKLEY DISCOVERED A SIDE DOOR OF THE STORAGE COMPARTMENT IN THE DELIVERY VEHICLE HAS OPENED AND  PACKAGE WAS MISSING SINCE THE LAST DELIVERY.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY IMPLEMENTED THE EMERGENCY PLAN.  THE ORIGINAL DRIVER FOUND THE PACKAGE ON THE ROAD. THE PACKAGE HADE BEEN DESTROYED.  THE PACKAGE WAS SURVEYED AND NO CONTAMINATION WAS FOUND.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SOME OF THE PACKAGING COMPONENTS WERE MISSING.  A SECURITY CAP WAS LOCATED BUT A GLASS VIAL WAS MISSING.  THE AREA WAS SURVEYED FOR THE MISSING VIAL WITHOUT SUCCESS. MEANWHILE, THERE WAS FREQUENT COMMUNICATION WITH THE SITE DIRECTOR.  THE SITE DIRECTOR MADE THE FOLLOWING CONTACTS:  A:  U.S NUCLEAR REGULATORY COMMISSION, REGION 1.  B: COMMONWEALTH OF MASSACHUSETTS, DEPT OF RADIATION PROTECTION.  C: DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER. ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE TO WAIT FOR THE DEPARTMENT OF RADIATION PROTECTION AT THE SCENE.  AT 4:00PM THE DEPARTMENT OF RADIATION PROTECTION AND CONSULTANTS OF LOWELL UNIVERSITY MET THE TRAFFIC DIRECTOR AND RADIATION SAFETY OFFICER.  THE CONSULTANTS LOCATED THE CRIMP SEAL, SEPTA AND BROKEN VIAL WITH THEIR METERING DEVICES.  THE CONSULTANTS REPORTED NO CONTAMINATION PROBLEM.    "MEETINGS HAVE BEEN HELD WITH ALL DELIVERY PERSONNEL TO REEMPHASIZE THE FOLLOWING POINTS:  BLOCKING AND BRACING OF ALL LOADS TO PREVENT MOVEMENT.  LOCKING ALL COMPARTMENT DOORS.  CHECKING COMPARTMENT DOORS.  CHECKING COMPARTMENT DOORS IN SIDE MIRRORS.  UNDER CONSIDERATION IS THE REDESIGN OF VEHICLE COMPARTMENT BRACES FOR BETTER PACKAGE RESTRAINT."

column168: THIS REPORT WAS LATE DUE TO A LOST PAPERWORK SHIPMENT.  LAS VEGAS FAA WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DELAY AND KEPT APPRAISED OF THE SITUATION. ATTACHMENT:   DURING THE OFF LOADING OF THE WCO FEEDER AIRCRAFT ON JULY 21, 1990, A LEAKING BOX WAS DISCOVERED.  THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS THICK AND MILKY LOOKING IN COLOR WITH A SLIGHT ODOR.  THERE WERE NO OUTER MARKINGS ON THE BOX TO INDICATE A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  WHEN THE BOX WAS OPENED THE CONTAINERS INSIDE HAD LEAKED BECAUSE OF THE PRESSURE CHANGE DURING FLIGHT.  THE NAME SINTOLIK WAS ON THE CONTAINER AND IT WAS MADE IN ITALY SO MOST OF THE INFORMATION WAS IN ITALIAN.  THERE WAS NO ONE INJURED AND NO PERMANENT DAMAGE TO THE AIRPLANE.  A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS CLEANED OUT OF THE PLANE WITH NO MORE THAN 1 HOUR OF TIME USED FOR CLEAN UP.  THE AIRCRAFT IS PARKED AT 241 E RENO IN LAS VEGAS, NEVADA 89119.  JUDY HARRISON, RAMP AGENT, LAS VEGAS.

UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD CUSTOMER SERVICE REPORTED THAT VAN WATERS AND ROGERS (CONSIGNEE) REQUESTED ASSISTANCE WITH TANK CAR GATX 25272.  WHEN PRESSURE WAS APPLIED TO IT FOR UNLOADING IT STARTED LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE MANWAY, THE PACKING GLAND OF THE TOP-OPERATED, BOTTOM OUTLET VAVLE CONTROL HANDLE, AND THE LIQUID EDUCTION VAVLE.  UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD SPECIAL AGENT-HAZADOUS MATERIALS, A. M. ROQUET, RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  A 3" LEAD RUPTURE DISC WITHOUT A BREATHER HOLE WAS FOUND IN THE SAFETY VENT. THE PACKING GLAND WAS LOOSE AND WHEN INSPECTED, SHOWED EVIDENCE OF NO PACKING MATERIAL PRESENT.  THE LIQUID EDUCTION VAVLE WAS TIGHT, BUT THE TEFLON PIPE TAPE PRESENT APPEARED INADEQUATE.  THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE SECURE.  WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF CONSIGNEE REPRESENTATIVES, TOM MACK, THE RUPTURE DISC WAS CHANGED TO STAINLESS STEEL 100#, THE PACKING GLAND WA PACKED GORTEX ROPE GASKET MATERIAL, AND THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE WAS RETAPED.  ALL FITTINGS WERE TIGHTENED DOWN, PRESSURE WAS APPLIED, AND NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS OBSERVED.  MS ROQUET NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND TRAIN MANAGEMENT- OMAHA
